# Prefer var for Local Variable Declarations

When declaring local variables in Java, prefer using `var` instead of explicit types when the type can be clearly inferred from the context.

## Guidelines:
- Use `var` for local variable declarations when the type is obvious from the right-hand side
- Use `var` to reduce verbosity and improve code readability
- Avoid `var` when it makes the code less clear or when the type is not obvious
- Do not use `var` for fields, method parameters, or method return types

## Examples:
```java
// Prefer this:
var list = new ArrayList<String>();
var map = new HashMap<String, Integer>();
var result = service.processData();

// Instead of:
ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<String>();
HashMap<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<String, Integer>();
ProcessResult result = service.processData();
```
